"Zamboni A., Murphy R.J., Woods J., Bezzo F., Shah N.","Biofuels carbon footprints: Whole-systems optimisation for GHG emissions reduction",2011,"Bioresource Technology","102","16",,"7457","7465",,,10.1016/j.biortech.2011.05.020,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959590256&partnerID=40&md5=243b9775cba7b19953eeccd30d0bf501","CAPE-Lab, Dipartimento di Principi e Impianti di Ingegneria Chimica, Università di Padova, Via Marzolo 9, I-35131 Padova, Italy; Division of Biology, Imperial College London, South Kensington Campus, SW7 2AZ London, United Kingdom; ICEPT - Centre for Energy Policy and Technology, Imperial College London, South Kensington, London SW7 2BP, United Kingdom; CPSE - Centre for Process Systems Engineering, Imperial College London, South Kensington Campus, London SW7 2AZ, United Kingdom","Zamboni, A., CAPE-Lab, Dipartimento di Principi e Impianti di Ingegneria Chimica, Università di Padova, Via Marzolo 9, I-35131 Padova, Italy; Murphy, R.J., Division of Biology, Imperial College London, South Kensington Campus, SW7 2AZ London, United Kingdom; Woods, J., ICEPT - Centre for Energy Policy and Technology, Imperial College London, South Kensington, London SW7 2BP, United Kingdom; Bezzo, F., CAPE-Lab, Dipartimento di Principi e Impianti di Ingegneria Chimica, Università di Padova, Via Marzolo 9, I-35131 Padova, Italy; Shah, N., CPSE - Centre for Process Systems Engineering, Imperial College London, South Kensington Campus, London SW7 2AZ, United Kingdom","A modelling approach for strategic design of ethanol production systems combining lifecycle analysis (LCA) and supply chain optimisation (SCO) can significantly contribute to assess their economic and environmental sustainability and to guide decision makers towards a more conscious implementation of ad hoc farming and processing practices. Most models applications so far have been descriptive in nature; the model proposed in this work is ""normative"" in that it aims to guide actions towards optimal outcomes (e.g. optimising the nitrogen balance through the whole supply chain). The modelling framework was conceived to steer strategic policies through a geographically specific design process considering economic and environmental criteria. Results shows how a crop management strategy devised from a whole systems perspective can significantly contribute to mitigate global warming even in first generation technologies. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Bioethanol; GHG emissions; Supply chain; Whole system optimisation","Carbon footprint; Crop managements; Decision makers; Environmental sustainability; Ethanol production; Generation technologies; GHG emission; Life cycle analysis; Modelling framework; Nitrogen balance; Optimisations; Specific design; Strategic design; Strategic policy; Whole systems; Bioethanol; Crops; Emission control; Ethanol; Global warming; Life cycle; Optimization; Supply chain management; Supply chains; Sustainable development; Greenhouse gases; alcohol; biofuel; action plan; agricultural management; biofuel; carbon emission; decision making; design method; ecological footprint; economic analysis; emission control; environmental economics; ethanol; global warming; greenhouse gas; life cycle analysis; numerical model; optimization; strategic approach; sustainability; alcohol production; article; carbon footprint; environmental sustainability; greenhouse effect; life cycle assessment; model; nitrogen balance; policy; priority journal; Biofuels; Carbon; Carbon Dioxide; Environmental Monitoring; Environmental Pollution; Greenhouse Effect",,"alcohol, 64-17-5; Biofuels; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9",,,,"http://www.agra-net.com, Agra Informa website:Berry, P.M., Kindred, D.R., Paveley, N.D., Quantifying the effects of fungicides and disease esistance on greenhouse gas emissions associated with wheat production (2008) Plant Pathol., 57, pp. 1000-1008; Brown, G., Wood, J., Estrin, A., (2005) Bioethanol Greenhouse Gas Calculator: Users' 